ub intermediate. It is a core convergence point in the network (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic Cu/H2S cyclization with ammonia release\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrolytic cyclization variant with NH3 release\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The same Cu/H2S-promoted ring closure and nitrile hydrolysis generates the cyclic hemiaminal while releasing ammonia as a byproduct.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the exact C1c variant reported by Patel et al. (2015). It is treated as a separate reaction node because the curated review identifies it as a distinct stoichiometric outcome, and it increases experimentally grounded route multiplicity to the target without inventing non-literature chemistry (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-mediated ring opening of the pyrimidine intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich cyanosulfidic solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN opens the cyclic hemiaminal ring, introducing a nitrile and yielding the linear cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the exact C2 transformation from Patel et al. (2015). The curated review flags ring-opening selectivity as an open question; the network therefore preserves this reaction as a likely selectivity-sensitive bottleneck while keeping the documented product identity unchanged (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile thiolysis to hydroxybutanethioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"elemental copper\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S in cyanosulfidic sulfur-rich setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thiolysis of nitrile under sulfur-rich surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen sulfide adds across the nitrile to form the corresponding thioamide while preserving the adjacent hydroxyl group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This exactly follows T1 in Patel et al. (2015): H2S converts the nitrile of the ring-opened intermediate into a thioamide, a hallmark cyanosulfidic transformation. The literature specifically identifies H2S as the key reagent for this step (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation of hydroxybutanethioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reductive dehydroxylation under cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu/H2S mediates elimination of the hydroxyl group as water, giving the deoxygenated thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the exact T2 transformation described by Patel et al. (2015), with copper and H2S explicitly required. The curated review notes copper availability as an open question; the network retains copper dependence rather than replacing it, in accordance with the literature constraints (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S thioamide-to-nitrile conversion to cyanohydrin-guanidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thioamide-to-nitrile exchange with HCN and water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A complex Cu/H2S-assisted exchange converts the thioamide terminus to a cyanohydrin nitrile, releasing H2S and NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This exactly reproduces T3 in Patel et al. (2015), one of the most distinctive steps in the arginine route. It regenerates hub reagents H2S and NH3 and produces the next major hub intermediate mol_014, helping explain network density while remaining faithful to the literature sequence (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of cyanohydrin-guanidine to arginine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface cyanosulfidic mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"amination with dissolved ammonia\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia replaces the hydroxyl group to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor bearing the complete arginine carbon and guanidine skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the exact F1 step from Patel et al. (2015), converting the cyanohydrin to the \u03b1-aminonitrile that directly precedes arginine. The curated review identifies this as the installation of the \u03b1-amino group characteristic of amino acids (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous surface mineral context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise nitrile hydrolysis; two water equivalents implicit from literature stoichiometry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis via an amide to the amino acid carboxylate, releasing ammonia and producing arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the exact F2 nitrile hydrolysis step reported by Patel et al. (2015), yielding arginine from the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor. The literature review notes that the sequence produces racemic arginine and that hydrolysis is compatible with wet-dry surface pool environments; the network preserves this endpoint without imposing enantioselectivity not present in the evidence (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical uptake of arginine into prebiotic pool inventory\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentration in prebiotic pools and protocell-compatible aqueous microenvironments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Physical transfer and ionization of arginine into concentrated prebiotic solution inventories enables downstream peptide and phosphate-binding chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review explicitly states that arginine produced in cyanosulfidic pools enters the prebiotic amino acid inventory and is relevant for peptide formation and phosphate interactions in proto-biological systems. This biochemical node is added only to complete the requested Surface \u2192 Biochemical interconnection and does not modify the synthesis route itself (Patel et al., 2015; curated review environmental context).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical arginine route via dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Literature-supported full Patel et al. route using the dry Cu/H2S cyclization variant.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical arginine route via hydrolytic cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Literature-supported full Patel et al. route using the hydrolytic Cu/H2S cyclization variant.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\