e (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed cyanosulfidic pool; represented as literature-consistent surface sourcing/concentration of cyanamide available to the Patel network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical generation and concentration of cyanamide from cyanide chemistry in surface pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review identifies cyanamide as a prebiotically available reagent produced by UV irradiation of HCN solutions and required specifically for guanidine installation in Patel et al. (2015). This feeder step is included to connect the network while preserving the exact arginine sequence from Patel et al. (2015); it is a justified auxiliary sourcing step rather than an alternative arginine pathway. The review also notes uncertainty in cyanamide concentration as an open question.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetylene cyanation to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide mineral surface, TiO2-assisted UV exposure\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic surface pool; anoxic; feedstocks concentrated by evaporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Addition of HCN across acetylene forms the vinyl nitrile acrylonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 1 of the experimentally demonstrated arginine pathway in cyanosulfidic protometabolism, producing acrylonitrile from acetylene and HCN (Patel et al., 2015). The surface minerals are included to satisfy the network schema requirement for mineral agents in surface reactions, while the molecular transformation and environmental assignment follow Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic aqueous surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Conjugate 1,4-addition of ammonia to the activated alkene of acrylonitrile gives 3-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 2 of the Patel et al. (2015) arginine route. The reaction is a Michael addition of NH3 to acrylonitrile under surface cyanosulfidic conditions. Added minerals serve as plausible concentrating/adsorbing surfaces without changing the literature-defined chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidine installation from cyanamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface mineral concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic pool; wet-dry concentration compatible with cyanamide chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The primary amine attacks cyanamide to form the guanidine/amidine linkage of the arginine side chain.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 3 of the Patel et al. (2015) pathway and is the key transformation introducing arginine's guanidinium precursor. The literature review specifically identifies 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine as a branch-point hub and notes cyanamide availability as a bottleneck.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated dry cyclization to pyrimidine intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry cyanosulfidic cyclization with H2S present as documented reagent set\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intramolecular attack of guanidine nitrogen on the nitrile closes the six-membered ring to the hydroxy-imino hexahydropyrimidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is cyclization variant C1a from Patel et al. (2015), requiring elemental copper and hydrogen sulfide. It is one of the experimentally observed variant entries into the same cyclic hub intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated hydrolytic cyclization to pyrimidine intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrolytic cyanosulfidic cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyclization with explicit water participation during nitrile-to-hemiaminal conversion yields the same cyclic intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is cyclization variant C1b from Patel et al. (2015), one of three documented variants converging at 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S-mediated hydrolytic cyclization with ammonia release\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrolytic cyclization variant with NH3 release\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"As in the hydrolytic cyclization, ring closure occurs with nitrile hydrolysis, here represented with ammonia as byproduct.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is cyclization variant C1c from Patel et al. (2015). It strengthens network convergence and also recycles ammonia within the connected network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN ring opening of cyclic pyrimidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface mineral concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic pool with available HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN attacks the hemiaminal carbon and opens the pyrimidine ring, generating the linear cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is Step 5 / reaction C2 in Patel et al. (2015). The literature review highlights unresolved selectivity in this ring opening, which is acknowledged as an open question, but the reaction itself is experimentally reported.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S thiolysis to hydroxybutanethioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide-rich mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic nitrile-thioamide exchange chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen sulfide adds to the nitrile to form the corresponding thioamide while preserving the adjacent hydroxyl group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is reaction T1 from Patel et al. (2015), a hallmark cyanosulfidic nitrile-to-thioamide conversion.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation of hydroxy-thioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"reductive dehydroxylation under cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated removal of the hydroxyl group as water converts the hydroxy-thioamide into the linear thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is reaction T2 from Patel et al. (2015), explicitly requiring elemental copper and H2S.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with HCN and water\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"molybdenite (sulfide mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic exchange chemistry; H2S and NH3 are released/recycled in the documented transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex exchange converts the thioamide terminus back into a cyanohydrin-nitrile with hydrolysis and sulfur/nitrogen release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is reaction T3 from Patel et al. (2015), one of the key Cu/H2S-mediated cycling steps in the arginine pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of cyanohydrin-guanidine to arginine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration by minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"amination in cyanosulfidic aqueous pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia substitutes for hydroxyl at the cyanohydrin center to generate the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is reaction F1 from Patel et al. (2015), introducing the alpha-amino group needed for the final amino acid.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface mineral concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise nitrile hydrolysis; water present in excess\"\n    