 this is included as a geochemical feeder step rather than a mechanistic molecular synthesis of H2S to avoid the stoichiometric problems noted in prior attempts. Surface arginine chemistry itself follows Patel et al. (2015); hydrothermal sulfide availability is consistent with the review's environmental interconnection discussion and broader vent geochemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal cyanide sourcing and export", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_002"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "represented as geochemical sourcing/availability and vent-to-surface transport under anoxic conditions, not as a single balanced synthetic transformation"}, "mechanism": "Hydrothermal redox processing and transport contribute reduced carbon/nitrogen feedstocks to surface environments.", "reasoning": "The literature review explicitly allows Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface transfer of HCN into cyanosulfidic pools. Because Patel et al. (2015) establishes the surface chemistry rather than a detailed hydrothermal HCN synthesis, this node is included as a geochemical sourcing/transport step needed for network connectivity and is intentionally framed non-stoichiometrically. This addresses the earlier criticism that hydrothermal feed reactions should be represented as sourcing, not implausible direct molecular reactions; the arginine-forming chemistry remains that of Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface cyanamide sourcing and concentration", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed cyanosulfidic pool; represented as literature-consistent surface sourcing/concentration of cyanamide available to the Patel network"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical generation and concentration of cyanamide from cyanide chemistry in surface pools.", "reasoning": "The literature review identifies cyanamide as a prebiotically available reagent produced by UV irradiation of HCN solutions and required specifically for guanidine installation in Patel et al. (2015). This feeder step is included to connect the network while preserving the exact arginine sequence from Patel et al. (2015); it is a justified auxiliary sourcing step rather than an alternative arginine pathway. The review also notes uncertainty in cyanamide concentration as an open question."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Acetylene cyanation to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["molybdenite (sulfide mineral)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mineral surface, TiO2-assisted UV exposure", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pool; anoxic; feedstocks concentrated by evaporation"}, "mechanism": "Addition of HCN across acetylene forms the vinyl nitrile acrylonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is Step 1 of the experimentally demonstrated arginine pathway in cyanosulfidic protometabolism, producing acrylonitrile from acetylene and HCN (Patel et al., 2015). The surface minerals are included to satisfy the network schema requirement for mineral agents in surface reactions, while the molecular transformation and environmental assignment follow Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "molybdenite (sulfide mineral)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic aqueous surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Conjugate 1,4-addition of ammonia to the activated alkene of acrylonitrile gives 3-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This is Step 2 of the Patel et al. (2015) arginine route. The reaction is a Michael addition of NH3 to acrylonitrile under surface cyanosulfidic conditions. Added minerals serve as plausible concentrating/adsorbing surfaces without changing the literature-defined chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Guanidine installation from cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic pool; wet-dry concentration compatible with cyanamide chemistry"}, "mechanism": "The primary amine attacks cyanamide to form the guanidine/amidine linkage of the arginine side chain.", "reasoning": "This is Step 3 of the Patel et al. (2015) pathway and is the key transformation introducing arginine's guanidinium precursor. The literature review specifically identifies 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine as a branch-point hub and notes cyanamide availability as a bottleneck."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated dry cyclization to pyrimidine intermediate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "molybdenite (sulfide mineral)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry cyanosulfidic cyclization with H2S present as documented reagent set"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular attack of guanidine nitrogen on the nitrile closes the six-membered ring to the hydroxy-imino hexahydropyrimidine.", "reasoning": "This is cyclization variant C1a from Pa