\": \"H2S-driven cyanosulfidic sulfur chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sulfide-rich surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2S adds to the nitrile to convert it into a thioamide while retaining the adjacent hydroxyl group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This nitrile-to-thioamide conversion is directly reported by Patel et al. (2015) and is a hallmark cyanosulfidic transformation. The Cu/H2S designation reflects the documented sulfur-rich copper-mediated system surrounding these transformations, although H2S is the immediate nucleophilic reagent in the literature (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation of hydroxy thioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"hydrogen sulfide\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"variable\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry compatible deoxygenation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/sulfide-mediated reductive elimination removes the hydroxyl group as water to form the linear thioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This exact dehydroxylation step is experimentally documented in Patel et al. (2015). It is one of the copper-dependent transformations highlighted as a challenge in the literature because copper availability may have constrained overall arginine production (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu/H2S thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with HCN and water\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper\", \"hydrogen sulfide\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper with H2S\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanosulfidic exchange chemistry with HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex exchange converts the thioamide back into a cyanohydrin/nitrile functionality, releasing H2S and NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) explicitly reports this unusual thioamide-to-nitrile cycling step as part of the arginine pathway. It creates another network hub by regenerating both H2S and NH3, which can be reused upstream or in downstream amination, enhancing internal connectivity without deviating from the literature (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of cyanohydrin guanidine to arginine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface mineral concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-rich cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia substitutes for the hydroxyl group, producing the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This penultimate literature-supported step is reported in Patel et al. (2015) and converts the cyanohydrin into the direct aminonitrile precursor to arginine. It establishes the alpha-amino stereocenter but remains racemic under prebiotic conditions, consistent with the review's chirality caveat (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface mineral concentration during aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise nitrile hydrolysis with water; net literature stoichiometry corresponds to 2 H2O\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise hydrolysis of the terminal nitrile through an amide to the carboxylic acid yields arginine with ammonia release.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) experimentally establishes final nitrile hydrolysis of the alpha-aminonitrile to arginine. This is the terminal target-forming step of all ten pathways in the network and conforms to the literature's Strecker-type hydrolysis logic. Water stoichiometry is condensed here at graph level while preserving the documented chemistry (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Transfer of arginine from surface pool to biochemical inventory\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"partitioning into concentrated prebiotic pools/protocell-compatible environments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Physical transfer and concentration of produced arginine into prebiotic pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature review explicitly states Surface -> Biochemical flow, with arginine entering the prebiotic amino acid inventory after cyanosulfidic synthesis. This reaction is therefore a network transition node rather than a new synthetic claim, included only to represent the required environmental interconnection while keeping the chemistry itself faithful to Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Peptide bond formation incorporating arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; illustrative downstream incorporation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of arginine with glycine forms a dipeptide and water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This downstream biochemical assembly step addresses the literature's statement that arginine produced in surface pools becomes available for peptide formation and phosphate-binding functions in prebiotic systems. It is included to complete the Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical story; the arginine synthesis itself remains entirely Patel et al. (2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide supply feeds the Patel et al. surface cyanosulfidic network, using cyclization variant A.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via hydrolytic cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Same Patel et al. route but proceeding through cyclization variant B.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release\",\n      \"description\": \"Patel et al. route using cyclization variant C, which also regenerates ammonia.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide plus internal NH3 recycling pathway A\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses hydrothermal sulfide input and explicitly exploits ammonia recycling from thioamide-to-nitrile conversion before final amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide plus dual NH3 regeneration pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant C cyclization and thioamide-to-nitrile conversion both regenerate ammonia within the same surface route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon linked pathway via dry cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"A connected network route where hydrothermal reduced-carbon generation is included as upstream environmental context feeding the same surface cyanosulfidic pool chemistry; cyclization variant A is used.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon linked pathway via hydrolytic cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Same connected environmental route but using cyclization variant B.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon linked pathway via NH3-releasing cyclization\",\n      \"description\": \"Connected environmental route with cyclization variant C and ammonia recycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduced-carbon linked pathway emphasizing thioamide cycling\",\n      \"description\": \"Highlights the distinctive nitrile-thioamide-nitrile cycling of the Patel et al. sequence from a hydrothermal-connected surface pool.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Full environmental interconnection to biochemical arginine inventory\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal sulfide sourcing, complete Patel et al. surface synthesis, then transfer of arginine into biochemical pools for peptide incorporation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_017\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network is anchored in the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic surface synthesis of arginine reported by Patel et al. (2015). To satisfy environmental interconnection without inventing chemically weak sourcing reactions, hydrothermal nodes are included only as geochemically plausible transport-linked feedstock generation steps for H2S and reduced carbon species, which then feed surface pool chemistry where the literature-supported 10-step arginine sequence occurs. Ten distinct pathways to arginine are represented as combinations of one of two hydrothermal sourcing routes with one of five surface branch variants/convergences in the Patel et al. sequence, all terminating in the same final nitrile hydrolysis to arginine. Hub molecules are hydrogen cyanide, ammonia, 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine, 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine, and 2-(4-amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "prop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "3-aminopropanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c4-2-1-3-5/h1-2,4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8N4", "iupac_name": "2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine", "common_name": "2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N4/c5-2-1-3-8-4(6)7/h1,3H2,(H4,6,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H9N3O", "iupac_name": "4-hydroxy-2-iminohexahydropyrimidine", "common_name": "4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9N3O/c5-4-6-2-1-3(8)7-4/h3,8H,1-2H2,(H3,5,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H10N4O", "iupac_name": "amino((3-cyano-3-hydroxypropyl)amino)methaniminium", "common_name": "ring-opened cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N4O/c6-3-4(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h4,10H,1-2H2,(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H12N4OS", "iupac_name": "4-(diaminomethylideneamino)-2-hydroxybutanethioamide", "common_name": "hydroxybutanethioamide guanidine intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N4OS/c6-4(11)3(10)1-2-9-5(7)8/h3,10H,1-2H2,(H2,6,11)(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H12N4S", "iupac_name": "4-(diaminomethylideneamino)butanethioamide", "common_name": "butanethioamide guanidine intermediate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N4S/c6-4(10)2-1-3-9-5(7)8/h1-3H2,(H2,6,10)(H4,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H12N4O", "iupac_name": "2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine", "common_name": "2-(4-cyano-4-hydroxybutyl)guanidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12N4O/c7-4-5(11)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h5,11H,1-3H2,(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H13N5", "iupac_name": "2-(4-amino-4-cyanobutyl)guanidine", "common_name": "arginine aminonitrile precursor", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H13N5/c7-4-5(8)2-1-3-11-6(9)10/h5H,1-3,8H2,(H4,9,10,11)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C6H14N4O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoic acid", "common_name": "arginine in prebiotic pool", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H14N4O2/c7-4(5(11)12)2-1-3-10-6(8)9/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,11,12)(H4,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C8H17N5O3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-N-(2-amino-5-(diaminomethylideneamino)pentanoyl)acetic acid", "common_name": "glycylarginine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; included only as geochemical reduced-carbon sourcing linked to transport into surface systems"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 to formate under vent redox gradients.", "reasoning": "FeS-family minerals are widely invoked for hydrothermal CO2 reduction and provide a plausible reduced-carbon source feeding broader prebiotic networks, while the arginine-forming sequence itself remains entirely surface cyanosulfidic as demonstrated experimentally. This reaction is included solely for environmental interconnection and not as an invented direct precursor step to arginine; the core arginine route follows Patel et al. (2015). Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on FeS minerals is supported by prebiotic vent literature including Huber & Wachtershauser (1997) and related iron-sulfur world studies; arginine-specific network core from Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal sulfide delivery to surface pools", "inputs": ["mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "represents hydrothermal vent liberation and transport of dissolved sulfide into connected surface waters; not a stoichiometric de novo synthesis claim"}, "mechanism": "Geochemical vent-associated release and transport of reduced sulfur species into anoxic aqueous systems.", "reasoning": "This node formalizes the literature-described Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface environmental interconnection for H2S supply without repeating chemically invalid water-to-H2S reactions. Patel et al. (2015) explicitly requires H2S in the cyanosulfidic arginine pathway, and the review notes hydrothermal and volcanic environments as plausible H2S sources. The reaction is therefore a network transport representation grounded in geochemical context rather than a speculative synthetic transformation; core arginine chemistry remains Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Acetylene cyanation to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["molybdenite (MoS2)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface cyanosulfidic mineral context", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions with UV-exposed feedstocks"}, "mechanism": "Addition of HCN across acetylene generates vinyl nitrile acrylonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the first experimentally documented arginine-specific step in the Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy & Sutherland (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway. The exact transformation acetylene + HCN -> acrylonitrile is taken directly from that study; the specified mineral agents here indicate required surface mineral context for the network schema while not replacing the literature-defined reagents and environment (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "molybdenite (MoS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "NH3 performs conjugate 1,4-addition to the beta-carbon of acrylonitrile to yield 3-aminopropanenitrile.", "reasoning": "This step follows Patel et al. (2015), where acrylonitrile reacts with ammonia to give 3-aminopropanenitrile. The transformation is central to building the amino nitrile backbone before guanidine installation; mineral agents are included only to satisfy network schema for surface settings and concentration on prebiotic surfaces, while the documented chemistry is from Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Guanidine installation from cyanamide", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic evaporitic pool conditions"}, "mechanism": "Primary amine of 3-aminopropanenitrile attacks cyanamide to form the guanidine linkage.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) directly demonstrated conversion of 3-aminopropanenitrile plus cyanamide to 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine. This is the decisive step introducing arginine's distinctive guanidinium precursor and is identified in the literature review as a key hub and possible bottleneck due to cyanamide availability (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated cyclization variant A (dry)", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper with H2S", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry cyclization under cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular attack of guanidine nitrogen on nitrile carbon closes a six-membered ring, giving the hydroxy-imino hexahydropyrimidine.", "reasoning": "This exact dry cyclization variant is one of the three Patel et al. (2015) experimentally reported ways to access the cyclic pyrimidine intermediate from 2-(2-cyanoethyl)guanidine. Copper/H2S mediation is specifically documented and is essential to literature fidelity (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated cyclization variant B (hydrolytic)", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper with H2S", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrolytic cyclization in cyanosulfidic pool"}, "mechanism": "Cyclization with explicit water participation in nitrile hydrolysis during ring closure forms the cyclic hemiaminal.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) reports this hydrolytic cyclization variant as an alternative experimentally supported route to the same cyclic intermediate. Retaining separate reaction nodes preserves the documented convergence on 4-hydroxy-2-imino-hexahydropyrimidine (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cu/H2S-mediated cyclization variant C with NH3 release", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper with H2S", "aqueous": "true", "other": "hydrolytic cyclization; ammonia released as byproduct"}, "mechanism": "Cyclization and hydrolytic hemiaminal formation proceed with ammonia liberation.", "reasoning": "This third cyclization variant is explicitly distinguished in Patel et al. (2015). Including it as a separate reaction is required by the literature review and creates one of the major network convergence/divergence points around the cyclic intermediate and ammonia recycling (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "HCN ring opening of cyclic pyrimidine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "molybdenite (MoS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface cyanosulfidic mineral context", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "HCN attacks the hemiaminal carbon, opening the ring and generating a linear cyanohydrin-guanidine intermediate.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) identifies this as the key ring-opening step that extends the carbon skeleton while introducing a new nitrile handle. The literature review notes regioselectivity here as an open question; this network follows the experimentally observed productive route without adding alternatives (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Nitrile thiolysis to hydroxy thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "H2S-driven cyanosulfidic sulfur chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sulfide-rich surface pool"}, "mechanism": "H2S adds to the nitrile to convert it into a thioamide while retaining the adjacent hydroxyl group.", "reasoning": "This nitrile-to-thioamide conversion is directly reported by Patel et al. (2015) and is a hallmark cyanosulfidic transformation. The Cu/H2S designation reflects the documented sulfur-rich copper-mediated system surrounding these transformations, although H2S is the immediate nucleophilic reagent in the literature (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cu/H2S reductive dehydroxylation of hydroxy thioamide", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper with H2S", "aqueous": "variable", "other": "wet-dry compatible deoxygenation"}, "mechanism": "Copper/sulfide-mediated reductive elimination removes the hydroxyl group as water to form the linear thioamide.", "reasoning": "This exact dehydroxylation step is experimentally documented in Patel et al. (2015). It is one of the copper-dependent transformations highlighted as a challenge in the literature because copper availability may have constrained overall arginine production (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cu/H2S thioamide-to-nitrile conversion with HCN and water", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper", "hydrogen sulfide"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper with H2S", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic exchange chemistry with HCN"}, "mechanism": "Complex exchange converts the thioamide back into a cyanohydrin/nitrile functionality, releasing H2S and NH3.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly reports this unusual thioamide-to-nitrile cycling step as part of the arginine pathway. It creates another network hub by regenerating both H2S and NH3, which can be reused upstream or in downstream amination, enhancing internal connectivity without deviating from the literature (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Amination of cyanohydrin guanidine to arginine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonia-rich cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia substitutes for the hydroxyl group, producing the alpha-aminonitrile precursor of arginine.", "reasoning": "This penultimate literature-supported step is reported in Patel et al. (2015) and converts the cyanohydrin into the direct aminonitrile precursor to arginine. It establishes the alpha-amino stereocenter but remains racemic under prebiotic conditions, consistent with the review's chirality caveat (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile to arginine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration during aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "stepwise nitrile hydrolysis with water; net literature stoichiometry corresponds to 2 H2O"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise hydrolysis of the terminal nitrile through an amide to the carboxylic acid yields arginine with ammonia release.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) experimentally establishes final nitrile hydrolysis of the alpha-aminonitrile to arginine. This is the terminal target-forming step of all ten pathways in the network and conforms to the literature's Strecker-type hydrolysis logic. Water stoichiometry is condensed here at graph level while preserving the documented chemistry (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Transfer of arginine from surface pool to biochemical inventory", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "partitioning into concentrated prebiotic pools/protocell-compatible environments"}, "mechanism": "Physical transfer and concentration of produced arginine into prebiotic pools.", "reasoning": "The literature review explicitly states Surface -> Biochemical flow, with arginine entering the prebiotic amino acid inventory after cyanosulfidic synthesis. This reaction is therefore a network transition node rather than a new synthetic claim, included only to represent the required environmental interconnection while keeping the chemistry itself faithful to Patel et al. (2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Peptide bond formation incorporating arginine", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_007"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; illustrative downstream incorporation"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of arginine with glycine forms a dipeptide and water.", "reasoning": "This downstream biochemical assembly step addresses the literature's statement that arginine produced in surface pools becomes available for peptide formation and phosphate-binding functions in prebiotic systems. It is included to complete the Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical story; the arginine synthesis itself remains entirely Patel et al. (2015)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via dry cyclization", "description": "Hydrothermal sulfide supply feeds the Patel et al. surface cyanosulfidic network, using cyclization variant A.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via hydrolytic cyclization", "description": "Same Patel et al. route but proceeding through cyclization variant B.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal sulfide-fed arginine pathway via hydrolytic cyclization with NH3 release", "description": "Patel et al. route using cyclization variant C, which also regenerates ammonia.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal sulfide plus internal NH3 recycling pathway A", "description": "Uses hydrothermal sulfide input and explicitly exploits ammonia recycling from thioamide-to-nitrile conversion before final amination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"]